1. Equality

The most basic form of comparison is equality. Letâ€™s briefly recap its syntax. The following statements all evaluate to TRUE.

Example:

rr 3 == (2 + 1) Â != TRUE != FALSE Â !=

Notice from the last expression that R is case sensitive: â€œRâ€ is not equal to â€œrâ€.

Comparison of numerics

Comparison of character strings

Â ==

Compare a logical with a numeric

TRUE == 1

Note the use of the double equal sign

Since TRUE coerces to 1 under the hood, TRUE == 1 evaluates to TRUE. Make sure not to mix up == (comparison) and = (assignment), == is what need to check the equality of R objects.

2. Greater and less than

less than and greater than operators: < and >. You can also add an equal sign to express less than or equal to or greater than or equal to, respectively. Have a look at the following R expressions, that all evaluate to FALSE:

rr (1 + 2) > 4 Â <
TRUE <= FALSE

R determines the greater than relationship based on alphabetical order.

TRUE is treated as 1 for arithmetic, and FALSE is treated as 0. Therefore, FALSE < TRUE is TRUE.
